1 Introduction

  • This is a notebook for hands-on sessions of the Social Network Analysis course for Ph.D.students of the Graduate School of Social and Political Sciences, University of Milan (Italy).
  • Analysed data are taken from Bianchi, Casnici, and Squazzoni (2018)

2 Collaboration

2.1 Loading data

  • Now, we need to import data on collaboration relationships.
  • In order to let R find the data, we need to move the data file to the same directory where our Rstudio project is located (i.e., the working directory)

If you dont remember what working directory youre in:

getwd()
## [1] "/Users/federico/Documents/sna-nasp/analysis"

  • Lets inspect the data structure: we could either open the file outside Rstudio or even from within

  • Its a .txt file. What do you see?

  • Its an adjacency matrix (see slides)

  • Values are 0 and 1 and are separated by a tab (\t)

  • In order to load it, we need a function to read a table data structure.

  • read.table is classic R, while readr::read_delim is faster. Lets load the readr package, included in the tidyverse.

# library(tidyverse)
library(readr)

Now we can inspect the read_delim function in the console, by hitting ?read_delim

?read_delim

What information do we need? * the file name: collaboration.txt * the column separator: "\t" * whether we have column names: no

Where is my data file?

dir()

In order to maximise reproducibility, we need the path to be available to all possible colleagues. We can use the here::here function, which builds a new path regardless of the original path. Lets load the here package.

library(here)
## here() starts at /Users/federico/Documents/sna-nasp/analysis

The function here() finds my working directory and builds a plausible path towards the specified arguments.

here("data", "collaboration.txt")
## [1] "/Users/federico/Documents/sna-nasp/analysis/data/collaboration.txt"

Now were ready to load collaboration data as a new object. We can use read_tsv, which takes "\t" as a default value of the delim parameter

collab.dat <- read_tsv(file = here("data", "collaboration.txt"), col_names = FALSE)
collab.dat

2.2 From data to graphs

library(igraph)

collaboration <- graph_from_adjacency_matrix(adjmatrix = collab.dat, mode = "undirected")

2.4.1 Density

  • In order to infer the level of connectivity from the number of edges, we need to compare it to the theoretically maximum value of possible links
  • We combine each vertex with all other possible vertices
  • Since our network is undirected, we divide by 2, so that we dont count pairs twice
  • Well store the calculation output in a new object because were going to use it later again and we want to stay D.R.Y.
max.links <- vcount(collaboration) * (vcount(collaboration) - 1) / 2
  • Now, we can calculate density as the ratio between the number of actual links and the number of possible links.
density <- ecount(collaboration) / max.links
  • Actually, we dont need to perform this calculation every time. There is a specific function in igraph
graph.density(collaboration)
## [1] 0.2019704

2.4.2 Discussion

  • Is the density value high or low? Is our collaboration network dense or sparse?
  • Lets compare with another network.

  • Why are nodes 28? We were expecting 29
  • One of the nodes might be an isolate
  • Its always good practice to store the list of edges and the list of nodes in two different objects, then integrate them in a graph object
  • The nodes are coded in the edge list file as V1, V2, , V29
  • So, well generate a character vector by combining V with numbers between 1-29
sup.edges <- sup.dat
sup.nodes <- paste0("V", 1:29)
sup.nodes
##  [1] "V1"  "V2"  "V3"  "V4"  "V5"  "V6"  "V7"  "V8"  "V9"  "V10" "V11" "V12"
## [13] "V13" "V14" "V15" "V16" "V17" "V18" "V19" "V20" "V21" "V22" "V23" "V24"
## [25] "V25" "V26" "V27" "V28" "V29"

Now we have a vector of nodes (node list) and a matrix of edges (edge list). We can then generate a graph object in a safer way through graph_from_data_frame, which takes a node list (vector) and and edge list (matrix) as inputs.

support <- graph_from_data_frame(d = sup.edges, vertices = sup.nodes)

4.1 Degree (undirected)

Degree of a graph vertex is its number of edges (= size of its personal network)

deg.col <- degree(collaboration)

## In- and out-degree (directed)

If the network is directed: * in-degree (popularity): number of arcs directed to a vertex * out-degree (activity): number of arcs directed away from a vertex

Lets look at the support network

sup.indeg <- degree(support, mode = "in")
hist(sup.indeg,
     col = "red",
     xlab = "In-degree",
     ylab = "Frequency",
     main = "Support",
     breaks = 0:max(sup.indeg)
     )

sup.outdeg <- degree(support, mode = "out")
hist(sup.outdeg,
     col = "blue",
     xlab = "Out-degree",
     ylab = "Frequency",
     main = "Support",
     breaks = 0:max(sup.outdeg)
     )

Lets plot both degree directions in the same chart: * We need ggplot(), which applies to data.frames or tibbles * Create a tibble with two columns (in- and out-degree) * In order to plot two variables in the same chart, we need to make it a tidy dataset: 1. Each variable must have its own column. 2. Each observation must have its own row. 3. Each value must have its own cell. * change dataset form to a longer form with degree in one variable and direction as the other variable
* now we can apply ggplot

library(tidyverse)
##  Attaching packages  tidyverse 1.3.0 
##  ggplot2 3.3.3      dplyr   1.0.5
##  tibble  3.1.0      stringr 1.4.0
##  tidyr   1.1.3      forcats 0.5.1
##  purrr   0.3.4
##  Conflicts  tidyverse_conflicts() 
## x dplyr::as_data_frame() masks tibble::as_data_frame(), igraph::as_data_frame()
## x purrr::compose()       masks igraph::compose()
## x tidyr::crossing()      masks igraph::crossing()
## x dplyr::filter()        masks stats::filter()
## x dplyr::groups()        masks igraph::groups()
## x dplyr::lag()           masks stats::lag()
## x purrr::simplify()      masks igraph::simplify()
df <- tibble(
  indegree = sup.indeg,
  outdegree = sup.outdeg
) %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = everything(),
    names_to = "direction", 
    values_to = "degree"
  )
     
df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = degree, fill = direction)) +
  geom_bar(position = "identity", alpha = .6) +
  theme_minimal() +
  ggtitle("Support: both degree directions")

6 Centrality

  • Which nodes are the most important ones?
  • Centrality is a (rather vague) concept of (structural) importance within a network
  • In a wider sense, a nodes degree can be seen as its degree centrality.

Plot collaboration network by emphasizing nodes degree centrality

collab.plot <- collaboration %>%

Creating a network object

sup.net <- network(x = as_adjacency_matrix(support), attributes)
## <sparse>[ <logic> ] : .M.sub.i.logical() maybe inefficient

Another way:

library(intergraph)
sup.net <- asNetwork(support)

Inspecting attributes and plotting

sup.net %v% "age"
##  [1] 40 41 25 28 28 31 39 28 31 28 33 52 31 27 31 31 32 31 34 40 28 31 24 27 31
## [26] 24 34 27 36
plot(sup.net)

sup.net %>% ggraph() + geom_node_point()
## Using `stress` as default layout

Reciprocal dyads

mutuality(sup.net) # number of complete dyads (pairs with reciprocal ties)
## Mut 
##  25
sna::dyad.census(sup.net) # 812 dyads, 406 pairs of nodes (29 * 28 / 2), 99 dyads with at least one tie, of which 25 are symmetrical, which means 50 ties are in symmetric dyads + 49 which are not in symmetric dyads = 99 dyads with a tie
##      Mut Asym Null
## [1,]  25   49  332

What should we compare it to?

  • fix number of nodes
  • assume a data-generating process

Lets compare it with a random network with 29 nodes. We need to specify a probability for ties to occur (lets pick density)

rnd.net <- rgraph(n = 29, m = 1, tprob = gden(sup.net))
gden(rnd.net)
## [1] 0.1317734
mutuality(rnd.net)
## Mut 
##   7
sna::dyad.census(rnd.net)
##      Mut Asym Null
## [1,]   7   93  306

Lets simulate a whole distribution of random graphs conditioned to n = 29 and probability = .12

rnd.net <- rgraph(n = 29, m = 1000, tprob = gden(sup.net))
hist(gden(rnd.net))

hist(mutuality(rnd.net), xlim = c(0, 30))
abline(v = mutuality(sup.net), col="blue")

Generate a U|L distribution of graphs conditioned on n and L

gr.list <- list()
for (i in seq_len(1000)) {
  gr.list[[i]] <- sample_gnm(vcount(support), ecount(support), directed = TRUE)
}

gr.list <- map(gr.list, ~ asNetwork(.x))

hist(mutuality(gr.list), breaks = 15, xlim = c(0,30))
abline(v = mutuality(sup.net), col="blue")

8 ERGM

  • Lets start by estimating an ERGM by specifying the baseline probability of edges to be present as only parameter

We first specify the formula of the first model were going to estimate

m0 <- sup.net ~ edges
m0
## sup.net ~ edges

Before fitting the model to our data, lets look at the value of the count statistics in our network related to the terms specified in m0

summary(m0)
## edges 
##    99

As we fit m0 to sup.net, our computer will look for the value of the \(\theta\) parameter that generates a distribution of random graphs with n = 99 nodes and L = 99 arcs as expected values

fit0 <- ergm(m0)
## Starting maximum pseudolikelihood estimation (MPLE):
## Evaluating the predictor and response matrix.
## Maximizing the pseudolikelihood.
## Finished MPLE.
## Stopping at the initial estimate.
## Evaluating log-likelihood at the estimate.
  • Computation was very quick because we havent assumed any dependencies between the data!
  • So, there is no need to use MCMC-MLE (Markov Chain Monte Carlo Maximum Likelihood Estimation)
  • Maximum Pseudo-Likelihood Estimation (MPLE) was emplyed, wich doesnt involve simulation
  • (see slides for more details on estimation)

Lets look at estimated coefficients and other relevant statistics

summary(fit0)
## Call:
## ergm(formula = m0)
## 
## Iterations:  5 out of 20 
## 
## Monte Carlo MLE Results:
##       Estimate Std. Error MCMC % z value Pr(>|z|)    
## edges  -1.9744     0.1073      0  -18.41   <1e-04 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
##      Null Deviance: 1125.7  on 812  degrees of freedom
##  Residual Deviance:  602.1  on 811  degrees of freedom
##  
## AIC: 604.1    BIC: 608.8    (Smaller is better.)

We can infer a negative tendency of ties to form, compared to a graph distribution generated by assuming independency between dyads. Random chance is 0.5, so no surprise to find a negative tendency. Its a social network, humans dont just form random ties with every other human they meet!

Lets retrieve the estimated coefficient values:

coef(fit0)
##     edges 
## -1.974362
  • From these estimates we can infer that the log-odds ln(p/(i-p)) of \(x_{ij} = 1\) is equal to coef(fit0)[1] * the change-statistic (\(\delta\)) in the model term, so that changing the local status of \(x_{ij}\) increases the global number of ties.
  • In this case, the change-statistic values is 1 because each tie addition increases the count-statistic of the edges term by 1

From log-odds to odds-ratio:

exp(coef(fit0)) / (1 + exp(coef(fit0)))
##     edges 
## 0.1219212

Its equal to the density of our network!

  • What we estimated so far is a model that generates a Bernouilli distribution, similar to the one derived by an Erds-Renyi model
  • Now its time to test the effect of reciprocity in our network
  • We do it by assuming dyadic dependency between the data (i.e., \(Pr(x_{ij})\) depends on \(Pr(x_{ji})\))
  • Then we estimate the value of the \(\theta\) parameter of a reciprocity term

Updating our model formula and checking count-statistics

m1 <- update.formula(m0, . ~ . + mutual)
summary(m1)
##  edges mutual 
##     99     25

Now we fit our model to the data. Our computer will look for the values of the \(\theta_1\) and \(\theta_2\) parameters that jointly generate a distribution of random graphs with n = 99 nodes, L = 99 arcs, and 25 reciprocated dyads as expected values

fit1 <- ergm(m1)

It took longer than the first model. In this case, MPLE wasnt powerful enough because we assumed dyadic dependency between our data, so MCMCMLE kicked in.

Lets look at estimated coefficients:

  • From this model, we can infer that sup.net is composed by a higher number of reciprocated dyads than random networks with .12 density
  • We can infer it from the positive value of the estimated coefficient of mutual and the fact that the estimated standard error (S.E.) is less than twice the size of the parameter effect
  • However, the large amount of reciprocated dyads might be due to other network processes generating an arc such that \(x_{ij} = 1\) where \(x_{ji} = 1\)
  • Lets check transitive closure (see slides), by adding geometrically weighted edgewise partners

Well start by defining an easily-interpretable fixed decay value of gwesp

m2 <- update.formula(m1, . ~ . + gwesp(.5, fixed = T))
summary(m2)
##           edges          mutual gwesp.fixed.0.5 
##        99.00000        25.00000        81.46703
  • Now the estimation procedure has taken much longer because dependencies between the data are more complex
  • The estimation might even have not converged.
  • One possible reason is that its difficult for our computer to generate a random graph distribution with 29 vertices, 99 arcs, 25 reciprocated dyads, and 81.47 as gwesp value with .5 decay parameter
  • In this case, might add new terms to the model that could help increase the global resemblance of the generated random graphs to our sup.net.
  • The twopath parameter often stabilizes the estimation process. Its also useful to estimate correct effects of transitive closure (see background reading)
m3 <- update.formula(m2, . ~ . + twopath)
summary(m3)
##           edges          mutual gwesp.fixed.0.5         twopath 
##        99.00000        25.00000        81.46703       306.00000
